{{italic title}} '''''The Cambridge Law Journal''''' ({{ISSN|0008-1973}}) is a [[Peer review|peer-reviewed]] academic [[law journal]] published by [[Cambridge University Press]]. It is the principal academic publication of the [[Faculty of Law, University of Cambridge|Faculty of Law]] of the [[University of Cambridge]]. Founded in 1921 it is the longest running university law journal in the United Kingdom .<ref>{{Cite web |title = Publications of the Cambridge Law Faculty |url = http://www.law.cam.ac.uk/about-the-faculty/publications.php |accessdate = 28 December 2009 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20091209052456/http://www.law.cam.ac.uk/about-the-faculty/publications.php# |archive-date = 2009-12-09 |dead-url = yes |df = }}</ref> Its current editor is [[John Bell (professor)|John Bell]].<ref>{{Cite web | title = Cambridge Law Journal Homepage | url = http://journals.cambridge.org/action/displayJournal?jid=CLJ | accessdate = 28 December 2009 }}</ref> Based on the outcomes of the 2001 [[Research Assessment Exercise]] a 2006 analysis ranked the journal as overall the 7th most influential in the United Kingdom.<ref>{{Cite journal | last = Campbell | first = Kevin |author2=Alan Goodacre |author3=Gavin Little | title = Ranking of United Kingdom Law Journals: An Analysis of the Research Assessment Exercise 2001 Submissions and Results | journal = Journal of Law and Society | volume = 33 | issue = 3 | pages = 335–363 | publisher = | location = | ssrn = 923186 | issn = | doi = 10.1111/j.1467-6478.2006.00362.x | id = }}</ref>
== History == The Cambridge Law Journal was founded as a student publication by the [[Cambridge University Law Society]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=|title=Cambridge Law Journal|jstor=4514852|journal=Cambridge Law Journal|volume=1|pages=|via=}}</ref> As it gained recognition for quality, its management was taken over by the [[Faculty of Law, University of Cambridge]].
